{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-single-post-js","path":"/still/","result":{"data":{"page":{"title":"Still","content":"\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><span class=\"wp-image-6823 inline-gatsby-image-wrapper gatsby-image-wrapper\" style=\"position:relative;overflow:hidden;max-width:100%;width:816px\" data-reactroot=\"\"><span aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"width:100%;padding-bottom:125.49019607843137%\"></span><img aria-hidden=\"true\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" alt=\"\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:0;transition-delay:500ms\"/><picture><source srcSet=\"/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/f5b77/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 204w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/d0be4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 408w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/b17a4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 816w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/5a523/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 816px) 100vw, 816px\"/><img sizes=\"(max-width: 816px) 100vw, 816px\" srcSet=\"/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/f5b77/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 204w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/d0be4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 408w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/b17a4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 816w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/5a523/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 1200w\" src=\"/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/b17a4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" loading=\"eager\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center;opacity:1;transition:opacity 500ms\"/></picture><noscript><picture><source srcset=\"/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/f5b77/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 204w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/d0be4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 408w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/b17a4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 816w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/5a523/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 816px) 100vw, 816px\" /><img loading=\"eager\" sizes=\"(max-width: 816px) 100vw, 816px\" srcset=\"/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/f5b77/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 204w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/d0be4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 408w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/b17a4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 816w,\n/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/5a523/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg 1200w\" src=\"/static/7922be6b9ed31c08548caf261bd9592b/b17a4/EricRhein_Communion-with-Oak_SelfPortrait_1998_1-1200x1506-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" style=\"position:absolute;top:0;left:0;opacity:1;width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;object-position:center\"/></picture></noscript></span></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Eric Rhein<br>Communion with Oak (self-portrait)<br>1998, gelatin silver print, 20”x16”</p>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n\n\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\"><i>I walk with the shadows</i></span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\"><i>of the men I’ve known,</i></span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\"><i>and loved, and tasted,</i></span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\"><i>and feel, even still,</i></span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\"><i>the warmth of their breath</i></span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\"><i>against my skin.</i></span></p>\n<p></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\">Eric Rhein<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><span class=\"s1\">1992</span></p>\n\n\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<p>_____________________</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Eric Rhein is an artist living and working in New York. He has exhibited widely in the United States and abroad, and has been reviewed in the <em>New York Times</em>, <em>Huffington Post</em>, <em>ARTnews</em>, <em>Vanity Fair</em>, and <em>Art in America</em>. He is included in the <em>Smithsonian Archives of American Art’s Visual Arts and the AIDS Epidemic: An Oral History Project. </em>He is a founding member of <em>Visual AIDS Archive Project</em>, and more of his work can be found on his <em><a href=\"https://visualaids.org/artists/eric-rhein\">Artist+ Registry</a></em> page.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Eric Rhein: Lifelines </em>is the forthcoming, full-length book on his work, to be published by <em>Institute 193</em>. This monograph will feature a series of luminous photographs showing the artist with friends and lovers, in an era when intimacy and sensuality between queer men was as central to their wellbeing as any medicine.&nbsp;</p>\n","link":"/still/","author":{"node":{"name":"Eric Rhein"}},"featuredImage":null,"categories":{"nodes":[{"slug":"leaf","ACFCategoryData":{"color":"#f1e2d2","colorHigh":"#353132","pageicon":{"localFile":{"publicURL":"/static/3a821b5009b6ffb46d8a4240b1b74687/leaf-page.png"}}}}]},"tags":{"nodes":[]}},"nextPage":{"title":"Why Make an ‘Open Work’?","uri":"/why-make-an-open-work/"},"previousPage":{"title":"1986: An Elegy for Our Coldest War","uri":"/1986-an-elegy-for-our-coldest-war/"}},"pageContext":{"id":"cG9zdDozNjA4","nextPage":"cG9zdDoxNjI3","previousPage":"cG9zdDozNzMz"}},"staticQueryHashes":["2005293003"]}